Probability Distributions in R

  • R provides a number of built-in functions for many probability distributions.
  • For each probability distribution there are four functions associated with it. They carry the prefixes
    • d: stands for density, returning the probability density function
    • p: stands for probability, returning the cumulative distribution function;
    • q: stands for quantile, returning the inverse of the cumulative distribution function; and
    • r: stands for random, returning random numbers following the specified probability distribution.
  • Below is an incomplete list of the available distributions for reference.

Normal Distribution

\[f(x;\mu,\sigma)= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi \sigma^2}}e^{\frac{(x-\mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}} \]

  • Next we introduce the R functions associated with the most commonly used probability distribution in Statistics: the normal distribution.
  • The associated R functions are dnorm(), pnorm(), qnorm() and rnorm().
  • Type ?dnorm in the R console for the detail of their usage.

dnorm()

  • The dnorm(x) function returns the density of the standard normal distribution (mean=0, standard deviation=1) at x.
  • The probability density function for the standard normal distribution is \[f(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi}}e^{x^2/2}\]
  • Example: dnorm(-4,4) returns the density \(f(x)\) at \(x = -4,-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2,3 \; \textrm{and}\; 4\). We see that the distribution is symmetric about \(x=0\).
dnorm(-4:4)
## [1] 0.0001338302 0.0044318484 0.0539909665 0.2419707245 0.3989422804
## [6] 0.2419707245 0.0539909665 0.0044318484 0.0001338302
  • You get the same numbers by plugging the numbers \(-4:4\) to the formula of the normal curve:
1/sqrt(2*pi)*exp(-(-4:4)^2/2)
## [1] 0.0001338302 0.0044318484 0.0539909665 0.2419707245 0.3989422804
## [6] 0.2419707245 0.0539909665 0.0044318484 0.0001338302

Normal Distribution

  • The standard normal curve can be plotted using the command
curve(dnorm(x), xlim=c(-4,4))

  • xlim=c(-4,4) tell R to plot the function in the range \(-4 \le x \le 4\). (Type ?curve to see the usage)
  • The dnorm() function has other options that allow you to specify the mean and standard deviation of the normal distributions.(Type ?dnorm to see the usage).
  • The mathematical equation for the distribution is \[f(x;\mu,\sigma)= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi \sigma^2}}e^{\frac{(x-\mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}} \]
curve(dnorm(x), xlim=c(-8,8))
curve(dnorm(x, mean=1, sd=2), col="red", add=TRUE)

  • The first line in the code chunk plots the standard normal curve (black curve) in the range \(8\le x \le 8\).
  • The second line in the code chunk plots the normal curve with mean (\(\mu = 1\)) and standard deviation (\(\sigma=2\)), with a red line specified by col="red".
  • The add=TRUE means that the plot should be added to the first plot instead of generating a new plot.

Normal Distribution

pnorm

  • The pnorm(z) function returns the cumulative probability of the standard normal distribution at Z score \(z\). (\(P(Z<z)\))
  • That is, its the area under the standard normal curve to the left of z (the area of the shaded blue region in the plot below).


- Example,

pnorm(1.65)
## [1] 0.9505285
  • This means, the probability of getting a Z score smaller than \(1.65\) is \(0.95\) or \(95\%\). (left-side tail)


- To find the area to the right (right-side tail), especially the case when we want to find the (one-sided) p-value corresponding to a Z score. We consider two methods.
1. \(P(Z>z)=P(Z<-z)\).
- Example 1) \(P(Z>1.65)=P(Z<-1.65)\)

pnorm(-1.65)
## [1] 0.04947147
  • Example 2) \(P(Z>1.65)=1-P(Z<1.65)\)
1-pnorm(1.65)
## [1] 0.04947147
  1. Use lower.tail=FALSE option in pnorm().
pnorm(1.65,lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 0.04947147

Normal Distribution

qnorm

  • The qnorm() function is the inverse of the pnorm() function: qnorm(y) returns the value x so that pnorm(x)=y.
  • Example, the Z score corresponding to the \(95^{th}\) percentile is
qnorm(0.95)
## [1] 1.644854
  • Interpretation: If you were to draw many samples from a standard normal distribution, you would expect that about 95% of those samples would have values less than 1.644854.
  • To confirm the result is correct:
pnorm( qnorm(0.95) )
## [1] 0.95
  • The lower.tail=FALSE option refers to the area of the right tail like the pnorm.
  • Example,
qnorm(0.05,lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 1.644854
  • This means that the Z score corresponding to the area of the right tail equaling 0.05 is 1.645.
  • By symmetry of the normal curve (the Z score is the negative of the Z score corresponding to the area of the left tail being 0.05). It can also be obtained by the following expression;
- qnorm(0.05)
## [1] 1.644854

\(\chi^2\) Distribution

  • If \(X_1, X_2, \cdots, X_k\) are independent random variables and they all follow the standard normal distribution, then the random variable \[ Q=X^2_1+X_2^2+ \cdots+ X_k^2 \] follows the \(\chi^2\) distribution with \(k\) degrees of freedom.
  • A \(\chi^2\) distribution with \(k\) degrees of freedom is constructed by the sum of the square of k independent, standard normal random variables.
  • The four functions associated with the \(\chi^2\) distribution are dchisq(), pchisq(), qchisq(), rchisq().
  • The usage is essentially the same as the four functions associated with the normal distribution.
  • Again, use ?dchisq to find out more information.
  • The probability density function of the \(\chi^2\) distribution can be found here.

\(\chi^2\) Distribution

dchisq()

  • To visualize the \(\chi^2\) distribution, we plot the density function using dchisq() at different degrees of freedom.
curve(dchisq(x,1),xlim=c(0,15),ylim=c(0,0.6),ylab="Chi Square Density")
curve(dchisq(x,2),col="red",lty=2,add=TRUE)
curve(dchisq(x,3),col="blue",lty=3,add=TRUE)
curve(dchisq(x,5),col="dark green",lty=4,add=TRUE)
curve(dchisq(x,10),col="brown",lty=5,add=TRUE)
legend(12,0.55,c("k=1","k=2","k=3","k=5","k=10"),
       col=c("black","red","blue","dark green","brown"),lty=1:5)

  • dchisq() requires at least 2 arguments. The first argument is the value of x we want to compute the density and the second one is the degree of freedom k.
  • \(\chi^2\) density functions with degrees of freedom k=1, 2, 3, 5 and 10 are plotted together in the plot above.
    • ylim is used to set the y-range of the plot;
    • ylab is used to change the y-axis label;
    • lty is used to change the line type (1=solid, 2=dashed, 3=dotted, 4=dash-dotted, 5=long-dashed);
    • legend() is used to display the legend.

\(\chi^2\) Distribution

pchisq()

  • pchisq(x,df) function returns the cumulative probability \(P(\chi^2 < x)\) for the \(\chi^2\) distribution with df degrees of freedom, i.e.the area of the shaded region in the plot of the \(\chi^2\) density curve below.

  • For the p-value calculation, we usually want the area of the tail, i.e.\(P(\chi^2 > x)\), the shaded region below.

  • We use pchisq(x,df,lower.tail=FALSE) or 1-pchisq(x,df).
  • Example, the p-value corresponding to \(\chi^2=21.78\) and \(df=10\) is
pchisq(21.78,10,lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 0.01626544

qchisq()

  • The qchisq() is the inverse of pchisq(): if pchisq(x)=y, then qchisq(y)=x.
  • Example, the \(\chi^2\) value corresponding to a \(5\%\) p-value and \(df=10\) is
qchisq(0.05,10,lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 18.30704

Students t Distribution

  • Let \(Z\) and \(W\) be two independent random variables where \(Z \sim N\) and \(W \sim \chi^2(k)\), then the random variable \[T= \frac{Z}{\sqrt{W/k}}\] is said to follow the t distribution with k degrees of freedom.

  • The four functions associated with the t distributions are dt(), pt(), qt() and rt().

  • The probability density function for the t distribution can be found here and in many textbooks.

  • We generate \(10^5\) random numbers following the t distribution with 5 df from the definition of the t distribution:

Z <- rnorm(1e5)
W <- rchisq(1e5,5)
T <- Z/sqrt(W/5)
  • We plot a histogram for the data:
hist(T,breaks=100,freq=FALSE)

Students t Distribution

dt()

  • Use the xlim parameter to exclude the region outside \((-5,5)\).
  • We plot the dt() function on the same graph.
hist(T, breaks=c(min(T), seq(-5,5,length.out=100), max(T)), freq=FALSE, xlim=c(-5,5))
curve(dt(x,5),col="red",add=TRUE)

  • From above, we observe the t distribution is symmetric about x=0 and resembles the normal curve.

  • You may recall from Stats class that the t distribution approaches the normal distribution when the degree of freedom \(k \rightarrow \infty\).

  • In general, the t curve falls more slowly than the normal curve at large \(|x|\).

  • The following code chunk plots the t curves with various degrees of freedom.

curve(dt(x,1),xlim=c(-5,5),ylim=c(0,0.4),ylab="Student's t Density")
curve(dt(x,2),col="red",lty=2,add=TRUE)
curve(dt(x,5),col="blue",lty=3,add=TRUE)
curve(dt(x,20),col="dark green",lty=4,add=TRUE)
curve(dnorm(x),col="brown",lty=5,add=TRUE)
legend(2,0.38,c("k=1","k=2","k=5","k=20","normal curve"),
       col=c("black","red","blue","dark green","brown"),lty=1:5)

Students t Distribution

pt() and qt()

  • pt() and qt() functions are used exactly the same way as the pchisq() and qchisq() functions.

  • P-value: The probability that a particular statistical measure, such as the mean or standard deviation, of an assumed probability distribution will be greater than or equal to observed results.

  • Example, the p-value corresponding to \(t=1.5\) and \(df=4\) is
pt(1.5,4,lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 0.104

  • This is also equal to pt(-1.5,4) since the t curve is symmetric.

  • The value of t corresponding to a p-value of \(5\%\) and \(df=4\) is

qt(0.05,4,lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 2.131847
  • This is also equal to -qt(0.05,4).
- qt(0.05,4)
## [1] 2.131847

Simulation

Generating Random Numbers

  • In statistics and other areas, the need to introduce randomness in processes and experiments is important.
  • Simulation is therefore an important topic.
  • Markov chain Monte Carlo, the bootstrap, random forests, bagging, etc. are some statistical procedure that requires random number generation or sampling during implementation.
  • Sometimes you want to simulate a system and random number generators can be used to model random inputs.
  • R comes with a set of pseuodo-random number generators that allow you to simulate from well known probability distributions like the Normal, Poisson, and binomial.
  • You might have observed we skipped rnorm(), rchisq(), rt() earlier. These functions are used to simulate random numbers for probability distributions in R
  • rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = 1) : generates \(n\) standard Normal random numbers with mean 0 and standard deviation 1.
  • rchisq(n,df) : generates \(n\) random numbers following the \(\chi^2\) distribution with df degrees of freedom.
  • rt(n,df) : generates \(n\) random numbers following the t distribution with df degrees of freedom.

  • When simulating any random numbers, we will want to be able reproduce the exact randomly generated numbers.
  • Setting the random number seed with set.seed() ensures reproducibility of the sequence of random numbers.
set.seed(107281)
y <- rnorm(10)

Simulation

Random Sampling

  • The sample() function draws randomly from a specified set of (scalar) objects allowing you to sample from arbitrary distributions of numbers.
set.seed(12345)
sample(1:10, 4)
## [1] 3 8 2 5
sample(1:10, 4)
## [1] 8 2 6 3
## Doesn't have to be numbers
sample(letters, 5)
## [1] "f" "g" "j" "q" "h"
## Sample w/replacement
sample(1:10, replace = TRUE)
##  [1]  7  6  1  4  8 10  3  9  4 10
  • Drawing samples from specific probability distributions can be done with r functions.
  • The sample() function can be used to draw random samples from arbitrary vectors.
  • Setting the random number generator seed via set.seed() is critical for reproducibility.
